<$fill $name="body">

! Patterns to copy

! 1. "Run a command" leaf — like souk21 / VS Code's command palette

```
title: $:/plugins/example/entries/save-wiki
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry
ca-name: Save Wiki
ca-icon: 💾
ca-kind: leaf
ca-order: 10
ca-actions: <$action-sendmessage $message="tm-save-wiki"/>
```

Type "save", Enter, done. No drills.

! 2. "Open a specific tiddler" via prefilled filter

A drill entry whose `ca-next-scope` returns a specific subset:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/entries/drafts
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry
ca-name: Drafts
ca-icon: 📝
ca-kind: drill
ca-order: 50
ca-next-scope: [has:field[draft.of]search<query>]
ca-next-title: Drafts
```

Right-arrow into "Drafts", type to narrow, Enter on a draft → standard tm-navigate opens it.

! 3. Type-narrowed search

```
title: $:/plugins/example/entries/persons
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry
ca-name: Persons
ca-kind: drill
ca-next-scope: [rrt.type[person]search<query>]
ca-next-entity-type: person
```

Paired with action tiddlers having `ca-entity-type: person`, Right-arrow (or Space) on a person opens the action menu.

! 4. Cross-entity drill chain

Persons → action menu → "Assigned Teams" (drill into person's teams) → Right-arrow a team → team's action menu → "Members" (drill into team's members) → Right-arrow a member → person's action menu (again, but for the new person).

The graph composes — no need to write a "Tasks of team members" macro; just hop through the existing edges.

! 5. Drill-then-act enum picker (mutation)

```
title: $:/plugins/example/actions/task/set-priority
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action
ca-entity-type: task
ca-name: Set Priority…
ca-kind: drill
ca-next-scope: [[low]] [[normal]] [[high]] [[critical]]
ca-next-default-action: <$action-setfield $tiddler=<<parent-picked>> priority=<<picked>>/>
```

User: Tasks → drill → highlight task → Right-arrow → "Set Priority…" → pick "high" → Enter → task.priority = "high".

! 6. List-append (multi-value field) mutation

```
title: $:/plugins/example/actions/meeting/add-participant
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/action
ca-entity-type: meeting
ca-name: Add Participant…
ca-kind: drill
ca-next-scope: [rrt.type[person]search<query>]
ca-next-default-action: <$action-listops $tiddler=<<parent-picked>> $field="participants" $subfilter="+[append<picked>]"/>
```

Uses `$action-listops` instead of `$action-setfield` to append rather than overwrite.

! 7. Section navigation (orga-apps / appify)

```
title: $:/plugins/example/entries/go-to-section
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry
ca-name: Go to Section…
ca-kind: drill
ca-next-scope: [[dashboard]] [[projects]] [[people]] [[orgas]]
ca-next-default-action: <$action-statewrap-navigate label=<<picked>> section=<<picked>>/>
```

The bare-string filter approach works for any small, static enumeration.

! 8. Pure axis chain — group by year / month / day

A view that buckets every non-system tiddler by created year, then month, then day. No recursive descent under the leaf buckets — day-rows are the tiddlers themselves.

```
title: $:/plugins/example/views/journal
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/view
ca-view-name: Journal
ca-view-roots: [!is[system]!is[shadow]]
ca-view-axes: $:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/axes/by-year-created $:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/axes/by-month-created $:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/axes/by-day-created
ca-view-row-actions: <$action-navigate $to=<<currentTiddler>>/>
ca-view-show-count: yes
ca-order: 600
```

The plugin's own ''By date'' view is the same shape with a slightly different ordering — fork it as `views/journal.tid` and tweak `roots` to scope to your journal namespace (e.g. `[prefix[journal/]]`).

! 9. Mixed — bucket the recursive tree

''By parent, sliced by year'' — TOC-tagged tiddlers grouped by their creation year, with each TOC then expanding its tag-subtree under the matching year:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/channels/by-parent-by-year
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/channel
ca-channel-name: By parent (by year)
ca-channel-roots: [tag[TableOfContents]]
ca-channel-children: [tag<currentTiddler>]
ca-channel-axes: $:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/axes/by-year-created
ca-channel-row-actions: <$action-navigate $to=<<currentTiddler>>/>
ca-channel-row-entity-type: [[tag-tree-node]]
```

```
title: $:/plugins/example/views/by-parent-yearly
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/view
ca-view-name: By parent (yearly)
ca-view-channels: $:/plugins/example/channels/by-parent-by-year
ca-view-sort: alphabetical
ca-view-containers-first: yes
ca-view-show-count: yes
ca-order: 700
```

Descent: root shows year buckets containing TOC tiddlers. Drill ''2026'' → TOC tiddlers created in 2026. Drill any TOC → its `tag<currentTiddler>` subtree, recursive — axes are exhausted; from here on it's standard ''By parent''.

Watch out: ''cross-bucket children.'' Inside the 2026 subtree, a child tiddler tagged with one of the 2026 TOCs may itself have been created in 2025 — the year bucketing only applies at the transition, not all the way down. Almost always what you want for tag-trees. If you need date-coherent descent, intersect a date predicate into `ca-channel-children` (e.g. `[tag<currentTiddler>get[created]format:date[YYYY]match<stage-1-picked>]`).

! 10. Group by an arbitrary field — parametric `by-field`

The shipped ''By field'' axis takes a `field` param at runtime. Add it via the picker → edit the state tiddler to fill in the field name:

```
title: $:/state/rimir/cascade-palette/channel-axes/by-tasks
type: application/json
{"axes":[{"title":"$:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/axes/by-field","params":{"field":"status"}}]}
```

This activates a ''By status'' grouping on whichever channel has slug `by-tasks`. For task lists, that produces buckets like ''open'' / ''in-progress'' / ''done'' — one per distinct value of the `status` field.

! 11. Custom axis — first tag as bucket

```
title: $:/plugins/example/axes/by-first-tag
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis
ca-axis-name: First tag
ca-axis-hint: Group by the first tag of each tiddler. Untagged rows land in the "—" bucket.
ca-axis-key: [tags[]first[]]
ca-axis-sort: asc
ca-axis-empty-label: untagged
```

Drop this on any channel's `ca-channel-axes` to bucket the channel's source by primary tag.

! 12. Custom axis — namespace prefix (first /-segment)

```
title: $:/plugins/example/axes/by-namespace-root
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/axis
ca-axis-name: Namespace root
ca-axis-key: [<currentTiddler>split[/]first[]]
ca-axis-sort: asc
ca-axis-empty-label: (top-level)
```

Combine with the existing ''By namespace'' children filter for a "namespace root → tree" two-level descent — bucket by top-level namespace, then descend each via path segments.

! 13. Row icon — open an external URL

The plugin ships a `url` row-icon out of the box; this is what it looks like:

```
title: $:/plugins/rimir/cascade-palette/row-icons/url
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/row-icon
ca-row-icon-key: url
ca-row-icon-glyph: 🌐
ca-row-icon-hint: Open external URL in a new tab
ca-row-icon-message: open-url
ca-row-icon-primary: yes
ca-row-icon-order: 10
```

The key `url` triggers a built-in resolver that scans the fields listed in `$:/config/rimir/cascade-palette/url-fields` (default `url`, space-separated). The first field whose value matches `^(?:https?|ftp|ftps|mailto|tel):` becomes `<<payload>>`; the message `open-url` opens it via `window.open(payload, "_blank", "noopener,noreferrer")`. Author your own URL field set by editing the config tiddler — e.g. `url website homepage source`.

! 14. Row icon — domain-specific deep-link

Surface a 🔗 on any tiddler that carries a `linear-ticket` field — Alt-↵ (or clicking the glyph) opens the matching ticket in Linear:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/row-icons/linear
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/row-icon
ca-row-icon-key: linear
ca-row-icon-glyph: 🔗
ca-row-icon-hint: Open Linear ticket
ca-row-icon-applies: [<currentTiddler>has[linear-ticket]]
ca-row-icon-payload: [<currentTiddler>get[linear-ticket]addprefix[https://linear.app/team/issue/]]
ca-row-icon-message: open-url
ca-row-icon-order: 20
```

Same shape works for Jira, GitHub PRs, Confluence pages — anything where a tiddler-side field can be transformed into a URL.

! 15. Row icon — fire wikitext actions instead of opening a URL

Row-icon actions aren't limited to URLs. The `ca-row-icon-action` field is plain wikitext fired through the page navigator — same context as `ca-actions`. Use it to mutate state, open tiddlers in the story river, send custom messages, etc.:

```
title: $:/plugins/example/row-icons/edit-raw
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/row-icon
ca-row-icon-key: edit-raw
ca-row-icon-glyph: ✎
ca-row-icon-hint: Open the raw editor
ca-row-icon-applies: [<currentTiddler>!is[system]]
ca-row-icon-action: <$action-sendmessage $message="tm-edit-tiddler" $param=<<currentTiddler>>/>
```

Every non-system tiddler gets a ✎ in its row-icon strip. Alt-↵ fires `tm-edit-tiddler` via the navigator — same effect as clicking the pencil in TW's storyline.

! 16. Filter operators — author-side reuse

The plugin ships four filter operators (`cp-child-of`, `cp-actions-for`, `cp-actions-applying-to`, `cp-position-of`) reachable from any wikitext, not just the palette engine. They are the supported entry point for plugins that want to integrate with the action catalogue without depending on the widget JS.

''Action-count badge for a kind preview pane''. The kind plugin's `palette/preview/instance-view.tid` can surface "N actions available" against the focused row by combining `cp-actions-applying-to` (filter path) with `cp-actions-for` (catalogue path) and counting the union:

```
<$let n={{{ [cp-actions-applying-to<currentTiddler>] [<currentTiddler>get[kind.type]cp-actions-for[]] +[unique[]count[]] }}}>
  {{$:/core/images/right-arrow}} <<n>> actions
</$let>
```

''Diagnostic: which actions surface for an arbitrary tiddler''. Drop this into a temporary tiddler and edit the `target` macro value:

```
\function target() Alice

! Catalogue (entity-type)
<$list filter="[<target>get[kind.type]cp-actions-for[]]" />

! Filter-applies
<$list filter="[cp-actions-applying-to<target>]" />
```

''Tree view: list entries placed under a parent in a named view''. Inverts the per-entry resolver into a per-parent query — useful for sanity-checking position fields:

```
\function parentTitle() Projects

<$list filter="[tag[$:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/entry]] :filter[cp-position-of[default]match<parentTitle>]" />
```

! 17. Channel "Overview" row — a summary you focus

Give a channel a summary pane that opens when its group is reached. The channel emits a synthetic ''Overview'' row leading its group; focusing it renders the named template in the side preview, and Enter moves focus into the pane.

```
title: $:/config/example/cascade-palette/channels/agenda
tags: $:/tags/rimir/cascade-palette/channel
ca-channel-name: Agenda
ca-channel-preview: Agenda
ca-channel-preview-name: ⏰ Agenda overview
ca-channel-preview-title: Upcoming — next 60 days
ca-channel-roots: [agenda-subjects[60]]
```

`Agenda` is an ordinary wikitext tiddler rendering the full summary (here via a custom `[agenda[60]]` filter operator) — it ignores `<<currentTiddler>>` because it's a fixed overview. Use `ca-view-preview` on a view instead to put one Overview row at the top of the whole result list rather than per-channel.

! What's NOT recommended

* ''Heavy filters in `ca-next-scope`'' — re-runs on every keystroke. If you can't avoid an expensive filter, cache the result in a state tiddler at palette-open time and have the scope read from the cache.
* ''Nested `$navigator` widgets in `ca-actions`'' — the engine already routes actions through the page's existing navigator. Wrapping your own navigator inside `ca-actions` won't change behaviour but adds noise.
* ''Side effects in `ca-next-scope` filters'' — TW filter operators are pure functions of tiddler state; don't try to write tiddlers from inside a scope filter. Use `ca-actions` / `ca-next-default-action` for mutations.

